724727f-b.title: Manhattan: West Street - 10th Street (West)
724727f-b.text:
(1)
West Street, east side, from West 10th (formerly Amos) Street,
opposite Pier 45, North River, to and including Charles Street,
opposite Pier 4o. The 1Cth Street corner is not quite all
included in the picture, at the right.
May 12, 1927.
L. Sperr.
NO REPRODUCTIONS.
(2)
The same, two years later. The Holland Hotel, on the north
corner of West 10th, has been brightened up. In the back-
ground, notice the old Beadleston s Woern Brewery, 10th to
Charles Streets.
March 8, 1929.
L. Sperr.
NO REPRODUCTIONS.

724324f-b.title: Manhattan: Weehawken Street - 10th Street (West)
724324f-b.text:
(1)
Weehawken Street, adjoining and south of the S.W. corner of West
10th Street, showing buildings bearing Nos. 393 to 388 West Street.
These structures have no Weehawken Street numbers. They are built on
the former site of the Weehawken Market which was erected subsequent
to the demolition of the old New York State Prison. This street
being cut through at that time. The Prison occupied this, and the
surrounding area between 1797 and 1829; this being its south western
section. See the New York Times, Sunday, August 22, 1937 for further
information.
March 8, 1929.

711056f-a.title: Manhattan: 10th Street (West) - West Street
711056f-a.text:
West 10th Street, west from Washington to West Streets, showing Pier
No. 45 North River at the foot of same. Note the elevated railroad bed
on Washington Street and the West Side Vehicular Express Highway on West  1
Street. Buildingi on the left (south side) are on a portion of the former
state prison site and will be demolished in the near future to permit the
erection of a 2-story garage.
May 29, 1936.
W.P.A. Photo.
Federal Art Froject.
